``\n\nNext, we compute `deriv g' t`. We have `g' = ∑ i, (y i - x i) * nth_partial i f ((1 - t) • x + t • y)`. This is a sum of terms of the form `(y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f) (z(t))`, where `z(t) = (1 - t) • x + t • y`. The derivative of this term with respect to `t` is `(y i - x i) * (deriv (nth_partial i f) (z(t)) * deriv z(t))`. Since `deriv (nth_partial i f) (z(t))` is the `i`-th partial derivative of `f` at `z(t)`, and `deriv z(t)` is the derivative of the point `z(t)` with respect to `t`, which is `y - x`. So the derivative is `(y i - x i) * (nth_partial i f (z(t)) * (y - x))`. The sum of these terms is `deriv g' t`. We also need `deriv g'' t`.\n\n```tactics\n  have eq2 : deriv g' 0 = g'' 0 := by\n    have eq3 : deriv g' 0 = deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) 0 := by simp [g']\n    have eq4 : deriv (interpolated_deriv x y f) 0 = g'' 0 := by\n      simp [interpolated_deriv2]\n      all_goals norm_num\n    rw [eq3, eq4]\n```\n\nNow we apply Taylor's theorem. The function `g` satisfies `g(t) = g(0) + g'(0)t + (1/2)g''(0)t^2 + R(t)`, where `R(t)` is the remainder term. We will use `deriv_eq_derivWithin_of_isOpen` and related theorems.\n\n```tactics\n  have h2 : f x - f y = - (g 1 - g 0) := by\n    rw [h1, h0]\n    all_goals ring\n```\n\nNow we express `g(1) - g(0)` using Taylor's theorem. We need to show that `g(1) - g(0) = (1/2)g''(0) + R(1)`, where `R(1)` is the remainder term.\n\n```tactics\n  have h3 : g 1 - g 0 = (1 / 2) * g'' 0 + (g 1 - g 0 - (1 / 2) * g'' 0) := by ring\n```\n\nThe remainder term `R(1)` can be bounded using the hypothesis `mpb` on the mixed partial derivatives. We also need to relate `g'' 0` to the sum of squares of partial derivatives.\n\n```tactics\n  have h4 : |g'' 0| ≤ 2 * (∑ i, |nth_partial i f x|) * ε := by\n    simp [g'']\n    have h5 : ∀ i j, |(nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) x| ≤ 2 * |nth_partial i f x| * |nth_partial j f x| := by\n      intro i j\n      have h5 : (nth_partial i <| nth_partial j f) x = (nth_partial j <| nth_parti