Now we can apply the chain rule for derivatives at a point.
The derivative of `f ∘ g` at `t` is `deriv f (g t) * deriv g t`.
Here, `g(t) = interpolator x y t`.
So `deriv (f ∘ g) t = deriv f (g t) * deriv g t`.
`deriv f (g t)` is the derivative of `f` at `g t`, which is `∑ i, (f i)'(g t) * (g t i)'`.
`deriv g t` is the derivative of `g` at `t`, which is `∑ i, (g i)'(t) * (t i)'`.
Since `t` is a scalar variable, `(t i)'` is `0` for all `i` except when `i` is the variable of differentiation (which is implicitly `0` in the derivative of a function of a single variable). Actually, we need the derivative of `g(t)` with respect to `t`.
`g(t) = (1 - t) • x + t • y`. The derivative of `g(t)` with respect to `t` is `y - x`.
So `deriv g t = y - x`.

Therefore, `deriv (f ∘ g) t = (deriv f (g t)) * (y - x)`.
`deriv f (g t)` is `∑ i, (f i)'(g t) * (g t i)'`.
`g t i = (1 - t) * x i + t * y i`. The derivative with respect to `t` is `y i - x i`.
So `deriv f (g t) = ∑ i, (f i)'(g t) * (y i - x i)`.
Therefore, `deriv (f ∘ g) t = (∑ i, (f i)'(g t) * (y i - x i)) * (y - x)`.
This is not the desired result.

